# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: compaction-geology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The term is derived from the name of the Greek god Aeolus, the keeper of the winds.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Aeolian processes are most important in areas where there is little or no vegetation.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] However, aeolian deposits are not restricted to arid climates.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] They are also seen along shorelines; along stream courses in semiarid climates; in areas of ample sand weathered from weakly cemented sandstone outcrops; and in areas of glacial outwash.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Loess, which is silt deposited by wind, is common in humid to subhumid climates.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Much of North America and Europe are underlain by sand and loess of Pleistocene age originating from glacial outwash.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The lee (downwind) side of river valleys in semiarid regions are often blanketed with sand and sand dunes.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Examples in North America include the Platte, Arkansas, and Missouri Rivers.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wind erodes the Earth's surface by *deflation* (the removal of loose, fine-grained particles by the turbulent action of the wind) and by *abrasion* (the wearing down of surfaces by the grinding action and sandblasting by windborne particles).
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Once entrained in the wind, collisions between particles further break them down, a process called *attrition*.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Worldwide, erosion by water is more important than erosion by wind, but wind erosion is important in semiarid and arid regions.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wind erosion is increased by some human activities, such as the use of 4x4 vehicles.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Deflation is the lifting and removal of loose material from the surface by wind turbulence.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] It takes place by three mechanisms: traction/surface creep, saltation, and suspension.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Traction or surface creep is a process of larger grains sliding or rolling across the surface.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Saltation refers to particles bouncing across the surface for short distances.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Suspended particles are fully entrained in the wind, which carries them for long distances.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Saltation likely accounts for 50–70 % of deflation, while suspension accounts for 30–40 % and surface creep accounts for 5–25 %.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Regions which experience intense and sustained erosion are called deflation zones.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Most aeolian deflation zones are composed of desert pavement, a sheet-like surface of rock fragments that remains after wind and water have removed the fine particles.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The rock mantle in desert pavements protects the underlying material from further deflation.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Areas of desert pavement form the *regs* or stony deserts of the Sahara.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] These are further divided into rocky areas called *hamadas* and areas of small rocks and gravel called *serirs*.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Desert pavement is extremely common in desert environments.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Blowouts are hollows formed by wind deflation.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Blowouts are generally small, but may be up to several kilometers in diameter.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The smallest are mere dimples 0.3 meters (1 ft) deep and 3 meters (10 ft) in diameter.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The largest include the blowout hollows of Mongolia, which can be 8 kilometers (5 mi) across and 60 to 100 meters (200 to 400 ft) deep.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Big Hollow in Wyoming, US, extends 14 by 9.7 kilometers (9 by 6 mi) and is up to 90 meters (300 ft) deep.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Abrasion (also sometimes called *corrasion*) is the process of wind-driven grains knocking or wearing material off of landforms.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] It was once considered a major contributor to desert erosion, but by the mid-20th Century, it had come to be considered much less important.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wind can normally lift sand only a short distance, with most windborne sand remaining within 50 centimeters (20 in) of the surface and practically none normally being carried above 2 meters (6 ft).
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Many desert features once attributed to wind abrasion, including wind caves, mushroom rocks, and the honeycomb weathering called tafoni, are now attributed to differential weathering, rainwash, deflation rather than abrasion, or other processes.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Abrasion produces polishing and pitting, grooving, shaping, and faceting of exposed surfaces.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] These are widespread in arid environments but geologically insignificant.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Polished or faceted surfaces called *ventifacts* are rare, requiring abundant sand, powerful winds, and a lack of vegetation for their formation.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] In parts of Antarctica wind-blown snowflakes that are technically sediments have also caused abrasion of exposed rocks.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Attrition is the wearing down by collisions of particles entrained in a moving fluid.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] It is effective at rounding sand grains and at giving them a distinctive *frosted* surface texture.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Collisions between windborne particles is a major source of dust in the size range of 2-5 microns.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Most of this is produced by the removal of a weathered clay coating from the grains.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wind dominates the transport of sand and finer sediments in arid environments.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wind transport is also important in periglacial areas, on river flood plains, and in coastal areas.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Coastal winds transport significant amounts of siliciclastic and carbonate sediments inland, while wind storms and dust storms can carry clay and silt particles great distances.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wind transports much of the sediments deposited in deep ocean basins.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] In *ergs* (desert sand seas), wind is very effective at transporting grains of sand size and smaller.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Particles are transported by winds through suspension, saltation (skipping or bouncing) and creeping (rolling or sliding) along the ground.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The minimum wind velocity to initiate transport is called the *fluid threshold* or *static threshold* and is the wind velocity required to begin dislodging grains from the surface.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Once transport is initiated, there is a cascade effect from grains tearing loose other grains, so that transport continues until the wind velocity drops below the *dynamic threshold* or *impact threshold*, which is usually less than the fluid threshold.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] In other words, there is hysteresis in the wind transport system.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Small particles may be held in the atmosphere in suspension.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Turbulent air motion supports the weight of suspended particles and allows them to be transported for great distances.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wind is particularly effective at separating sediment grains under 0.05 mm in size from coarser grains as suspended particles.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Saltation is downwind movement of particles in a series of jumps or skips.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Saltation is most important for grains of up to 2 mm in size.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] A saltating grain may hit other grains that jump up to continue the saltation.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The grain may also hit larger grains (over 2 mm in size) that are too heavy to hop, but that slowly creep forward as they are pushed by saltating grains.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Surface creep accounts for as much as 25 percent of grain movement in a desert.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Vegetation is effective at suppressing aeolian transport.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Vegetation cover of as little as 15% is sufficient to eliminate most sand transport.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The size of shore dunes is limited mostly by the amount of open space between vegetated areas.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Aeolian transport from deserts plays an important role in ecosystems globally.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] For example, wind transports minerals from the Sahara to the Amazon basin.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Saharan dust is also responsible for forming red clay soils in southern Europe.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Dust storms are wind storms that have entrained enough dust to reduce visibility to less than 1 kilometer (0.6 mi).
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Most occur on the synoptic (regional) scale, due to strong winds along weather fronts, or locally from downbursts from thunderstorms.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Crops, people, and possibly even climates are affected by dust storms.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] On Earth, dust can cross entire oceans, as occurs with dust from the Sahara that reaches the Amazon Basin.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Dust storms on Mars periodically engulf the entire planet.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] When the Mariner 9 spacecraft entered its orbit around Mars in 1971, a dust storm lasting one month covered the entire planet, thus delaying the task of photo-mapping the planet's surface.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Most of the dust carried by dust storms is in the form of silt-size particles.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Deposits of this windblown silt are known as loess.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The thickest known deposit of loess, up to 350 meters (1,150 ft), is on the Loess Plateau in China.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] This very same Asian dust is blown for thousands of miles, forming deep beds in places as far away as Hawaii.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The Peoria Loess of North America is up to 40 meters (130 ft) thick in parts of western Iowa.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The soils developed on loess are generally highly productive for agriculture.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Small whirlwinds, called dust devils, are common in arid lands and are thought to be related to very intense local heating of the air that results in instabilities of the air mass.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Dust devils may be as much as one kilometer high.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Dust devils on Mars have been observed as high as 10 kilometers (6.2 mi), though this is uncommon.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wind is very effective at separating sand from silt and clay.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] As a result, there are distinct sandy (erg) and silty (loess) aeolian deposits, with only limited interbedding between the two.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Loess deposits are found further from the original source of sediments than ergs.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] An example of this is the Sand Hills of Nebraska, US.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Here vegetation-stabilized sand dunes are found to the west and loess deposits to the east, further from the original sediment source in the Ogallala Formation at the feet of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Some of the most significant experimental measurements on aeolian landforms were performed by Ralph Alger Bagnold, a British army engineer who worked in Egypt prior to World War II.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Bagnold investigated the physics of particles moving through the atmosphere and deposited by wind.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] He recognized two basic dune types, the crescentic dune, which he called "barchan", and the linear dune, which he called longitudinal or "seif" (Arabic for "sword").
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Bagnold developed a classification scheme that included small-scale ripples and sand sheets as well as various types of dunes.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Bagnold's classification is most applicable in areas devoid of vegetation.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] In 1941, John Tilton Hack added parabolic dunes, which are strongly influenced by vegetation, to the list of dune types.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The discovery of dunes on Mars reinvigorated aeolian process research, which increasingly makes use of computer simulation.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wind-deposited materials hold clues to past as well as to present wind directions and intensities.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] These features help us understand the present climate and the forces that molded it.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] For example, vast inactive ergs in much of the modern world attest to late Pleistocene trade wind belts being much expanded during the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Ice cores show a tenfold increase in non-volcanic dust during glacial maxima.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The highest dust peak in the Vostok ice cores dates to 20 to 21 thousand years ago.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The abundant dust is attributed to a vigorous low-latitude wind system plus more exposed continental shelf due to low sea levels.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wind-deposited sand bodies occur as ripples and other small-scale features, sand sheets, and dunes.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wind blowing on a sand surface ripples the surface into crests and troughs whose long axes are perpendicular to the wind direction.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The average length of jumps during saltation corresponds to the wavelength, or distance between adjacent crests, of the ripples.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] In ripples, the coarsest materials collect at the crests causing inverse grading.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] This distinguishes small ripples from dunes, where the coarsest materials are generally in the troughs.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] This is also a distinguishing feature between water laid ripples and aeolian ripples.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] A *sand shadow* is an accumulation of sand on the downwind side of an obstruction, such as a boulder or an isolated patch of vegetation.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Here the sand builds up to the angle of repose (the maximum stable slope angle), about 34 degrees, then begins sliding down the *slip face* of the patch.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] A *sandfall* is a sand shadow of a cliff or escarpment.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Closely related to sand shadows are *sand drifts*.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] These form downwind of a gap between obstructions, due to the funneling effect of the obstructions on the wind.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Sand sheets are flat or gently undulating sandy deposits with only small surface ripples.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] An example is the Selima Sand Sheet in the eastern Sahara Desert, which occupies 60,000 square kilometers (23,000 sq mi) in southern Egypt and northern Sudan.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] This consists of a few feet of sand resting on bedrock.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Sand sheets are often remarkably flat and are sometimes described as *desert peneplains*.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Sand sheets are common in desert environments, particularly on the margins of dune fields, although they also occur within ergs.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Conditions that favor the formation of sand sheets, instead of dunes, may include surface cementation, a high water table, the effects of vegetation, periodic flooding, or sediments rich in grains too coarse for effective saltation.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] A dune is an accumulations of sediment blown by the wind into a mound or ridge.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] They differ from sand shadows or sand drifts in that they are independent of any topographic obstacle.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Dunes have gentle upwind slopes on the windward side.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The downwind portion of the dune, the lee slope, is commonly a steep avalanche slope referred to as a slipface.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The minimum height of a slipface is about 30 centimeters.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wind-blown sand moves up the gentle upwind side of the dune by saltation or creep.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Sand accumulates at the brink, the top of the slipface.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] When the buildup of sand at the brink exceeds the angle of repose, a small avalanche of grains slides down the slipface.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Grain by grain, the dune moves downwind.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Linear dunes, also called longitudinal dunes or seifs, are aligned in the direction of the prevailing winds.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Transverse dunes, which include crescent dunes (barchans), are aligned perpendicular to the prevailing winds.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] More complex dunes, such as star dunes, form where the directions of the winds are highly variable.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Additional dune types arise from various kinds of topographic forcing, such as from isolated hills or escarpments.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Transverse dunes occur in areas dominated by a single direction of the prevailing wind.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] In areas where sand is not abundant, transverse dunes take the form of barchans or crescent dunes.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] These are not common, but they are highly recognizable, with a distinctive crescent shape with the tips of the crescent directed downwind.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The dunes are widely separated by areas of bedrock or reg.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Barchans migrate up to 30 meters (98 ft) per year, with the taller dunes migrating faster.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Barchans first form when some minor topographic feature creates a sand patch.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] This grows into a sand mound, and the converging streamlines of the air flow around the mound build it into the distinctive crescent shape.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Growth is ultimately limited by the carrying capacity of the wind, which as the wind becomes saturated with sediments, builds up the slip face of the dune.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Because barchans develop in areas of limited sand availability, they are poorly preserved in the geologic record.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Where sand is more abundant, transverse dunes take the form of aklé dunes, such as those of the western Sahara.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] These form a network of sinuous ridges perpendicular to the wind direction.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Aklé dunes are preserved in the geologic record as sandstone with large sets of cross-bedding and many reactivation surfaces.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Draas are very large composite transverse dunes.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] They can be up to 4,000 meters (13,000 ft) across and 400 meters (1,300 ft) high and extend lengthwise for hundreds of kilometers.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] In form, they resemble a large aklé or barchanoid dune.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] They form over a prolonged period of time in areas of abundant sand and show a complex internal structure.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Careful 3-D mapping is required to determine the morphology of a draa preserved in the geologic record.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Linear dunes can be traced up to tens of kilometers, with heights sometimes in excess of 70 meters (230 ft).
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] They are typically several hundred meters across and are spaced 1 to 2 kilometers (0.62 to 1.24 mi) apart.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] They sometimes coalesce at a Y-junction with the fork directed upwind.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] They have a sharp sinuous or en echelon crest.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] They are thought to form from a bimodal seasonal wind pattern, with a weak wind season characterized by wind directed an at acute angle to the prevailing winds of the strong wind season.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The strong wind season produces a barchan form and the weak wind season stretches this into the linear form.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Another possibility is that these dunes result from secondary flow, though the precise mechanism remains uncertain.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Complex dunes (star dunes or rhourd dunes) are characterized by having more than two slip faces.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] They consist of a central peak with radiating crests and are thought to form where strong winds can come from any direction.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Those in Gran Desierto de Altar of Mexico are thought to have formed from precursor linear dunes due to a change in the wind pattern about 3000 years ago.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Complex dunes show little lateral growth but strong vertical growth and are important sand sinks.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Vegetated parabolic dunes are crescent-shaped, but the ends of the crescent point upwind, not downwind.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] They form from the interaction of vegetation patches with active sand sources, such as blowouts.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The vegetation stabilizes the arms of the dune, and an elongated lake sometimes forms between the arms of the dune.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Clay dunes are uncommon but have been found in Africa, Australia, and along the Gulf Coast of North America.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] These form on mud flats on the margins of saline bodies of water subject to strong prevailing winds during a dry season.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Clay particles are bound into sand-sized pellets by salts and are then deposited in the dunes, where the return of the cool season allows the pellets to absorb moisture and become bound to the dune surface.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Deserts cover 20 to 25 percent of the modern land surface of the earth, mostly between the latitudes of 10 to 30 degrees north or south.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Here the descending part of the tropical atmospheric circulation (the Hadley cell) produces high atmospheric pressure and suppresses precipitation.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Large areas of this desert is floored with windblown sand.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Such areas are called *ergs* when they exceed about 125 square kilometers (48 sq mi) in area or *dune fields* when smaller.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Ergs and dune fields make up about 20% of modern deserts or about 6% of the Earth's total land surface.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The sandy areas of today's world are somewhat anomalous.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Deserts, in both the present day and in the geological record, are usually dominated by alluvial fans rather than dune fields.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The present relative abundance of sandy areas may reflect reworking of Tertiary sediments following the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Most modern deserts have experienced extreme Quaternary climate change, and the sediments that are now being churned by wind systems were generated in upland areas during previous pluvial (moist) periods and transported to depositional basins by stream flow.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The sediments, already sorted during their initial fluvial transport, were further sorted by wind, which also sculpted the sediments into eolian landforms.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The state of an aeolian system depends mainly on three things: The amount of sediment supply, the availability of sediments, and the transport capacity of the winds.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The sediment supply is largely produced in pluvial periods (periods of greater rainfall) and accumulates by runoff as fan deltas or terminal fans in sedimentary basins.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Another important source of sediments is the reworking of carbonate sediments on continental shelves exposed during times of lower sea level.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Sediment availability depends on the coarseness of the local sediment supply, the degree of exposure of sediment grains, the amount of soil moisture, and the extent of vegetation coverage.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The potential transport rate of wind is usually more than the actual transport, because the sediment supply is usually insufficient to saturate the wind.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] In other words, most aeolian systems are *transport-undersaturated* (or *sediment-undersaturated*).
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Aeolian desert systems can be divided into wet, dry, or stabilized systems.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Dry systems have the water table well below the surface, where it has no stabilizing effect on sediments.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Dune shapes determine whether sediment is deposited, simply moves across surface (a *bypass* system), or erosion takes place.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Wet systems are characterized by a water table near the depositional surface, which exerts a strong control on deposition, bypass, or erosion.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Stabilized systems have significant vegetation, surface cement, or mud drapes which dominate the evolution of the system.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The Sahara shows the full range of all three types.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The movement of sediments in aeolian systems can be represented by sand-flow maps.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] These are based on meteorological observations, bedform orientations, and trends of yardangs.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] They are analogous to drainage maps, but are not as closely tied to topography, since wind can blow sand significant distances uphill.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The Sahara of North Africa is the largest hot desert in the world.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Flowlines can be traced from erg to erg, demonstrating very long transport downwind.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Satellite observations show yardangs aligned with the sandflow lines.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] All flowlines arise in the desert itself, and show indications of clockwise circulation roughly like high pressure cells.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The greatest deflation occurs in dried lake beds where trade winds form a low-level jet between the Tibesti Mountains and the Ennedi Plateau.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The flowlines eventually reach the, sea creating great plume of Saharan dust extending thousands of kilometers into the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] This creates a steady rain of silt into the ocean.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] It is estimated that 260 million tons of sediments are transported through this system each year, but the amount was much greater during the Last Glacial Maximum, based on deep-sea cores.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Mineral dust of 0.1–1 microns in size is a good shortwave radiation scatterer and has a cooling effect on climate.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Another example of an aeolian system is the arid interior of Australia.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] With few topographic barriers to sand movement, an anticlockwise wind system is traced by systems of longitudinal dunes.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The Namib and Oman ergs are fed by coastal sediments.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The Namib receives its sediments from the south through narrow deflation corridors from coast that cross more than 100 kilometers (62 mi) of bedrock to the erg.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The Oman was created by deflation of marine shelf carbonates during the last Pleistocene lowstand of the sea.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The Loess Plateau of China has been a long-term sink for sediments during the Quaternary ice age.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] It provides a record of glaciation, in the form of glacial loess layers separated by paleosols (fossil soils).
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The loess layers were desposited by a strong northwest winter monsoon, while the paleosols record the influence of a moist southeast monsoon.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The African savannah is mostly ergs deposited during the Last Glacial Maximum that are now stabilized by vegetation.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Aeolian processes can be discerned at work in the geologic record as long ago as the Precambrian.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Aeolian formations are prominent in the Paleozoic and Mesozoic of the western US.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Perhaps the best examples of aeolian processes in the geologic record are the Jurassic ergs of the western US.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] These include the Wingate Sandstone, the Navajo Sandstone, and the Page Sandstone.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Individual formations are separated by regional unconformities indicate erg stabilization.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The ergs interfingered with adjacent river systems, as with the Wingate Sandstone interfingering with the Moenave Formation and the Navajo Sandstone with the Kayenta Formation.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The Navajo and Nugget Sandstones were part of the largest erg deposit in the geologic record.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] These formations are up to 700 meters (2,300 ft) thick and are exposed over 265,000 square kilometers (102,000 sq mi).
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Their original extent was likely 2.5 times the present outcrop area.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Though once thought to possibly be marine in origin, they are now all but universally regarded as aeolian deposits.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] They are made up mostly of fine- to medium-sized quartz grains that are well-rounded and frosted, both indications of aeolian transport.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The Navajo contains huge tabular crossbed sets with sweeping foresets.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Individual crossbed sets dip at an angle of more than 20 degrees and are from 5 to 35 meters (16 to 115 ft) thick.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The formation contains freshwater invertebrate fossils and vertebrate tracks.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Slump structures (contorted bedding) are present that resemble those in modern wetted dunes.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Successive migrating dunes deposited a vertical stacking of eolian beds between interdune bounding surfaces and regional supersurfaces.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The Permian Rotliegend Group of the North Sea and north Europe contains sediments from adjacent uplands.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Erg sand bodies within the group are up to 500 meters (1,600 ft) thick.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Study of the crossbedding shows that sediments were deposited by a clockwise atmospheric cell.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Drilling core show dry and wet interdune surfaces and regional supersurfaces, and provide evidence of five or more cycles of erg expansion and contraction.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] A global rise in sea level finally drowned the erg and deposited the beds of the Weissliegend.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The Cedar Mesa Sandstone in Utah was contemporary with the Rogliegend.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] This formation records at least 12 erg sequences bounded by regional deflation supersurfaces.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] Aeolian landforms preserved in the formation range from damp sandsheet and lake paleosol (fossil soil) beds to thin, chaotically arranged dune sets to equilibrium erg construction, with dunes 300 to 400 meters (980 to 1,310 ft) wide migrating over still larger draas.
[src:compaction-geology/aeolian-processes] The draas survived individual climate cycles, and their interdunes were sites of barchan nucleation during arid portions of the climate cycles.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] In structural geology, an **anticline** is a type of fold that is an arch-like shape and has its oldest beds at its core, whereas a syncline is the inverse of an anticline.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] A typical anticline is convex up in which the hinge or crest is the location where the curvature is greatest, and the limbs are the sides of the fold that dip away from the hinge.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Anticlines can be recognized and differentiated from **antiforms** by a sequence of rock layers that become progressively older toward the center of the fold.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Therefore, if age relationships between various rock strata are unknown, the term antiform should be used.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The progressing age of the rock strata towards the core and uplifted center, are the trademark indications for evidence of anticlines on a geological map.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] These formations occur because anticlinal ridges typically develop above thrust faults during crustal deformations.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The uplifted core of the fold causes compression of strata that preferentially erodes to a deeper stratigraphic level relative to the topographically lower flanks.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Motion along the fault including both shortening and extension of tectonic plates, usually also deforms strata near the fault.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] This can result in an asymmetrical or overturned fold.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] An **antiform** can be used to describe any fold that is convex up.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] It is the relative ages of the rock strata that distinguish anticlines from antiforms.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The *hinge* of an anticline refers to the location where the curvature is greatest, also called the *crest*.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The hinge is also the highest point on a stratum along the top of the fold.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The *culmination* also refers to the highest point along any geologic structure.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The *limbs* are the sides of the fold that display less curvature.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The *inflection point* is the area on the limbs where the curvature changes direction.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The *axial surface* is an imaginary plane connecting the hinge of each layer of rock stratum through the cross section of an anticline.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] If the axial surface is vertical and the angles on each side of the fold are equivalent, then the anticline is symmetrical.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] If the axial plane is tilted or offset, then the anticline is asymmetrical.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] An anticline that is cylindrical has a well-defined axial surface, whereas non-cylindrical anticlines are too complex to have a single axial plane.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] An **overturned anticline** is an asymmetrical anticline with a limb that has been tilted beyond perpendicular, so that the beds in that limb have basically flipped over and may dip in the same direction on both sides of the axial plane.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] If the angle between the limbs is large (70–120 degrees), then the fold is an **"open" fold**, but if the angle between the limbs is small (30 degrees or less), then the fold is a **"tight" fold**.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] If an anticline plunges (i.e., the anticline crest is inclined to the Earth's surface), it will form *V*s on a geological map view that point in the direction of plunge.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] A **plunging anticline** has a hinge that is not parallel to the earth's surface.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] All anticlines and synclines have some degree of plunge.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] **Periclinal folds** are a type of anticlines that have a well-defined, but curved hinge line and are doubly plunging and thus elongate domes.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Folds in which the limbs dip toward the hinge and display a more U-like shape are called *synclines*.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] They usually flank the sides of anticlines and display opposite characteristics.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] A syncline's oldest rock strata are in its outer limbs; the rocks become progressively younger toward its hinge.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] A *monocline* is a bend in the strata resulting in a local steepening in only one direction of dip.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Monoclines have the shape of a carpet draped over a stairstep.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] An anticline that has been more deeply eroded in the center is called a **breached or scalped anticline**.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Breached anticlines can become incised by stream erosion, forming an anticlinal valley.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] A structure that plunges in all directions to form a circular or elongate structure is a *dome*.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Domes may be created via diapirism from underlying magmatic intrusions or upwardly mobile, mechanically ductile material such as rock salt (salt dome) and shale (shale diapir) that cause deformations and uplift in the surface rock.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The Richat Structure of the Sahara is considered a dome that has been laid bare by erosion.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] An anticline which plunges at both ends is termed a **doubly plunging anticline**, and may be formed from multiple deformations, or superposition of two sets of folds.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] It may also be related to the geometry of the underlying detachment fault and the varying amount of displacement along the surface of that detachment fault.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] An **anticlinorium** is a large anticline in which a series of minor anticlinal folds are superimposed.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Examples include the Late Jurassic to Early Cretaceous Purcell Anticlinorium in British Columbia and the Blue Ridge anticlinorium of northern Virginia and Maryland in the Appalachians, or the Nittany Valley in central Pennsylvania.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Anticlines are usually developed above thrust faults, so any small compression and motion within the inner crust can have large effects on the upper rock stratum.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Stresses developed during mountain building or during other tectonic processes can similarly warp or bend bedding and foliation (or other planar features).
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The more the underlying fault is tectonically uplifted, the more the strata will be deformed and must adapt to new shapes.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The shape formed will also be very dependent on the properties and cohesion of the different types of rock within each layer.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] During the formation of flexural-slip folds, the different rock layers form parallel-slip folds to accommodate for buckling.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] A good way to visualize how the multiple layers are manipulated, is to bend a deck of cards and to imagine each card as a layer of rock stratum.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The amount of slip on each side of the anticline increases from the hinge to the inflection point.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Passive-flow folds form when the rock is so soft that it behaves like weak plastic and slowly flows.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] In this process different parts of the rock body move at different rates causing shear stress to gradually shift from layer to layer.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] There is no mechanical contrast between layers in this type of fold.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Passive-flow folds are extremely dependent on the rock composition of the stratum and can typically occur in areas with high temperatures.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Anticlines, structural domes, fault zones and stratigraphic traps are very favorable locations for oil and natural gas drilling.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] About 80 percent of the world's petroleum has been found in anticlinal traps.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The low density of petroleum causes oil to buoyantly migrate out of its source rock and upward toward the surface until it is trapped and stored in reservoir rock such as sandstone or porous limestone.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The oil becomes trapped along with water and natural gas by a caprock that is made up of impermeable barrier such as an impermeable stratum or fault zone.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Examples of low-permeability seals that contain the hydrocarbons, oil and gas, in the ground include shale, limestone, sandstone, and rock salt.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The actual type of stratum does not matter as long as it has low permeability.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Water, minerals and specific rock strata such as limestone found inside anticlines are also extracted and commercialized.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Lastly, ancient fossils are often found in anticlines and are used for paleontological research or harvested into products to be sold.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Ghawar Anticline, Saudi Arabia, the structural trap for the largest conventional oil field in the world.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The Weald–Artois Anticline is a major anticline which outcrops in southeast England and northern France.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] It was formed from the late Oligocene to middle Miocene, during the Alpine orogeny.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Anticlines can have a major effect on the local geomorphology and economy of the regions in which they occur.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] One example of this is the El Dorado anticline in Kansas.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The anticline was first tapped into for its petroleum in 1918.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Soon after the site became a very prosperous area for entrepreneurs following World War I and the rapid popularization of motor vehicles.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] By 1995 the El Dorado oil fields had produced 300 million barrels of oil.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The central Kansas uplift is an antiform composed of several small anticlines that have collectively produced more than 2.5 million barrels of oil.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Another notable anticline is the Tierra Amarilla anticline in San Ysidro, New Mexico.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] This is a popular hiking and biking site because of the great biodiversity, geologic beauty and paleontological resources.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] This plunging anticline is made up of Petrified Forest mudstones and sandstone and its caprock is made of Pleistocene and Holocene travertine.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The anticline contains springs that deposit carbon dioxide travertine that help to contribute to the rich diversity of microorganisms.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] This area also contains remains of fossils and ancient plants from the Jurassic period that are sometimes exposed through geological erosion.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The Ventura Anticline is a geologic structure that is part of the Ventura oil fields, the seventh largest oil field in California that was discovered in the 1860s.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The anticline runs east to west for 16 miles, dipping steeply 30–60 degrees at both ends.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Ventura County has a high rate of compression and seismic activity due to the converging San Andreas Fault.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] As a result, the Ventura anticline rises at a rate of 5 mm/year with the adjacent Ventura Basin converging at a rate of about 7–10 mm/year.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The anticline is composed of a series of sandstone rock beds and an impermeable rock cap under which vast reserves of oil and gas are trapped.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] Eight different oil bearing zones along the anticline vary greatly from 3,500 to 12,000 feet.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] The oil and gas formed these pools as they migrated upward during the Pliocene Era and became contained beneath the caprock.
[src:compaction-geology/anticline] This oil field is still active and has a cumulative production of one billion barrels of oil making it one of the most vital historical and economic features of Ventura County.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] A **carbonate** is a salt of carbonic acid, (H2CO3), characterized by the presence of the **carbonate ion**, a polyatomic ion with the formula CO2−3.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] The word "carbonate" may also refer to a carbonate ester, an organic compound containing the **carbonate group** O=C(−O−)2.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] In geology and mineralogy, the term "carbonate" can refer both to carbonate minerals and carbonate rock (which is made of chiefly carbonate minerals), and both are dominated by the carbonate ion, CO2−3.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Carbonate minerals are extremely varied and ubiquitous in chemically precipitated sedimentary rock.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] The most common are calcite or calcium carbonate, CaCO3, the chief constituent of limestone (as well as the main component of mollusc shells and coral skeletons); dolomite, a calcium-magnesium carbonate CaMg(CO3)2; and siderite, or iron(II) carbonate, FeCO3, an important iron ore.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Sodium carbonate ("soda" or "natron"), Na2CO3, and potassium carbonate ("potash"), K2CO3, have been used since antiquity for cleaning and preservation, as well as for the manufacture of glass.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Carbonates are widely used in industry, such as in iron smelting, as a raw material for Portland cement and lime manufacture, in the composition of ceramic glazes, and more.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] New applications of alkali metal carbonates include thermal energy storage and use as catalysts and electrolytes both in molten carbonate fuel cells and in electrosynthesis of H2O2 in aqueous media.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] The carbonate ion is the simplest oxocarbon anion.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] It consists of one carbon atom surrounded by three oxygen atoms, in a trigonal planar arrangement, with *D*3h molecular symmetry.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] It has a molecular mass of 60.01 g/mol and carries a total formal charge of −2.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] It is the conjugate base of the hydrogencarbonate (bicarbonate) ion, HCO−3, which is the conjugate base of H2CO3, carbonic acid.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] The Lewis structure of the carbonate ion has two (long) single bonds to negative oxygen atoms, and one short double bond to a neutral oxygen atom.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] This structure is incompatible with the observed symmetry of the ion, which implies that the three bonds are the same length and that the three oxygen atoms are equivalent.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Metal carbonates generally decompose on heating, liberating carbon dioxide and leaving behind an oxide of the metal.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] As illustrated by its affinity for Ca2+, carbonate is a ligand for many metal cations.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Transition metal carbonate and bicarbonate complexes feature metal ions covalently bonded to carbonate in a variety of bonding modes.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Lithium, sodium, potassium, rubidium, caesium, and ammonium carbonates are water-soluble salts, but carbonates of 2+ and 3+ ions are often poorly soluble in water.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Of the insoluble metal carbonates, CaCO3 is important because, in the form of scale, it accumulates in and impedes flow through pipes.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Hard water is rich in this material, giving rise to the need for infrastructural water softening.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Thus, limescale can be removed with acid.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] In solution the equilibrium between carbonate, bicarbonate, carbon dioxide and carbonic acid is sensitive to pH, temperature, and pressure.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Although di- and trivalent carbonates have low solubility, bicarbonate salts are far more soluble.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] This difference is related to the disparate lattice energies of solids composed of mono- vs dianions, as well as mono- vs dications.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] In aqueous solution, carbonate, bicarbonate, carbon dioxide, and carbonic acid participate in a dynamic equilibrium.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] In strongly basic conditions, the carbonate ion predominates, while in weakly basic conditions, the bicarbonate ion is prevalent.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] In more acid conditions, aqueous carbon dioxide, CO2(aq), is the main form, which, with water, H2O, is in equilibrium with carbonic acid – the equilibrium lies strongly towards carbon dioxide.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Thus sodium carbonate is basic, sodium bicarbonate is weakly basic, while carbon dioxide itself is a weak acid.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] In organic chemistry a carbonate can also refer to a functional group within a larger molecule that contains a carbon atom bound to three oxygen atoms, one of which is double bonded.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] These compounds are also known as organocarbonates or carbonate esters, and have the general formula R−O−C(=O)−O−R′, or RR′CO3.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Important organocarbonates include dimethyl carbonate, the cyclic compounds ethylene carbonate and propylene carbonate, and the phosgene replacement, triphosgene.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Exhaled CO2(g) depletes CO2(aq), which in turn consumes H2CO3, causing the equilibrium of the first reaction to try to restore the level of carbonic acid by reacting bicarbonate with a hydrogen ion, an example of Le Châtelier's principle.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] The result is to make the blood more alkaline (raise pH).
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] By the same principle, when the pH is too high, the kidneys excrete bicarbonate (HCO−3) into urine as urea via the urea cycle (or Krebs–Henseleit ornithine cycle).
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] By removing the bicarbonate, more H+ is generated from carbonic acid (H2CO3), which comes from CO2(g) produced by cellular respiration.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Crucially, a similar buffer operates in the oceans.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] It is a major factor in climate change and the long-term carbon cycle, due to the large number of marine organisms (especially coral) which are made of calcium carbonate.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Increased solubility of carbonate through increased temperatures results in lower production of marine calcite and increased concentration of atmospheric carbon dioxide.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] This, in turn, increases Earth temperature.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] The amount of CO2−3 available is on a geological scale and substantial quantities may eventually be redissolved into the sea and released to the atmosphere, increasing CO2 levels even more.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] It is generally thought that the presence of carbonates in rock is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Recent observations of the planetary nebula NGC 6302 show evidence for carbonates in space, where aqueous alteration similar to that on Earth is unlikely.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Other minerals have been proposed which would fit the observations.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Small amounts of carbonate deposits have been found on Mars via spectral imaging and Martian meteorites also contain small amounts.
[src:compaction-geology/carbonate] Groundwater may have existed at Gusev and Meridiani Planum.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] In sedimentology, **compaction** is the process by which a sediment progressively loses its porosity due to the effects of pressure from loading.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] This forms part of the process of lithification.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] When a layer of sediment is originally deposited, it contains an open framework of particles with the pore space being usually filled with water.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] As more sediment is deposited above the layer, the effect of the increased loading is to increase the particle-to-particle stresses resulting in porosity reduction primarily through a more efficient packing of the particles and to a lesser extent through elastic compression and pressure solution.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] The initial porosity of a sediment depends on its lithology.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] Mudstones start with porosities of >60%, sandstones typically ~40% and carbonates sometimes as high as 70%.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] Results from hydrocarbon exploration wells show clear porosity reduction trends with depth.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] Compaction trend estimation and decompaction process are useful for analyzing numerical basin evolution (e.g., subsidence) and evaluating hydrocarbon reservoirs and geological storages.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] In sediments compacted under self-weight, especially in sedimentary basins, the porosity profiles often show an exponential decrease, called Athy's law as first shown by Athy in 1930.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] A mathematical analytical solution was obtained by Fowler and Yang to show the theoretical basis for Athy's law.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] This process can be easily observed in experiments and used as a good approximation to many real data.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] If there is a variation in thickness and compactability of a sequence, loading by later deposits will give rise to spatially varying amounts of compaction.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] This form of compaction is a function of the lithology of the base sediment.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] Both the thickness and structure of the later sequence will be controlled by the underlying geology in the absence of any active tectonics.
[src:compaction-geology/compaction-geology] Buried tilted fault blocks in a rift basin often produce large anticlinal closures in the post-rift section that may form traps for hydrocarbons e.g. the Daqing Field, the largest oil field in the People's Republic of China, in the Songliao Basin.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] In the narrow sense, "consolidation" refers strictly to this delayed volumetric response to pressure change due to gradual movement of water.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Some publications also use "consolidation" in the broad sense, to refer to any process by which soil changes volume due to a change in applied pressure.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] This broader definition encompasses the overall concept of soil compaction, subsidence, and heave.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Some types of soil, mainly those rich in organic matter, show significant creep, whereby the soil changes volume slowly at constant effective stress over a longer time-scale than consolidation due to the diffusion of water.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] To distinguish between the two mechanisms, "primary consolidation" refers to consolidation due to dissipation of excess water pressure, while "secondary consolidation" refers to the creep process.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The effects of consolidation are most conspicuous where a building sits over a layer of soil with low stiffness and low permeability, such as marine clay, leading to large settlement over many years.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Types of construction project where consolidation often poses technical risk include land reclamation, the construction of embankments, and tunnel and basement excavation in clay.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Geotechnical engineers use oedometers to quantify the effects of consolidation.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] In an oedometer test, a series of known pressures are applied to a thin disc of soil sample, and the change of sample thickness with time is recorded.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] This allows the consolidation characteristics of the soil to be quantified in terms of the coefficient of consolidation ( $C_{v}$ ) and hydraulic conductivity ( K ).
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Clays undergo consolidation settlement not only by the action of *external* loads (surcharge loads) but also under its own weight or weight of soils that exist above the clay.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Clays also undergo settlement when dewatered (groundwater pumping) because the effective stress on the clay increases.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Coarse-grained soils do not undergo consolidation settlement due to relatively high hydraulic conductivity compared to clays.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Instead, coarse-grained soils undergo the immediate settlement.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The first modern theoretical models for soil consolidation were proposed in the 1920s by Terzaghi and Fillunger, according to two substantially different approaches.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The former was based on diffusion equations in eulerian notation, whereas the latter considered the local Newton's law for both liquid and solid phases, in which main variables, such as partial pressure, porosity, local velocity etc., were involved by means of the mixture theory.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Fillunger's model was very abstract and involved variables that were difficult to detect experimentally, and, therefore, it was not applicable to the study of real cases by engineers and/or designers.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Nevertheless, this provided the basis for advanced theoretical studies of particularly complex problems.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Due to the different approach to the problem of consolidation by the two scientists, a bitter scientific dispute arose between them, and this unfortunately led to a tragic ending in 1937.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] After Fillunger's suicide, his theoretical results were forgotten for decades, whereas the methods proposed by Terzaghi found widespread diffusion among scientists and professionals.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] In the following decades Biot fully developed the three-dimensional soil consolidation theory, extending the one-dimensional model previously proposed by Terzaghi to more general hypotheses and introducing the set of basic equations of poroelasticity.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] According to the "father of soil mechanics", Karl von Terzaghi, consolidation is "any process which involves a decrease in water content of saturated soil without replacement of water by air".
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] More generally, consolidation refers to the process by which soils change volume in response to a change in pressure, encompassing both compaction and swelling.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Consolidation is the process in which reduction in volume takes place by the gradual expulsion or absorption of water under long-term static loads.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] When stress is applied to a soil, it causes the soil particles to pack together more tightly.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] When this occurs in a soil that is saturated with water, water will be squeezed out of the soil.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The magnitude of consolidation can be predicted by many different methods.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] In the classical method developed by Terzaghi, soils are tested with an oedometer test to determine their compressibility.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] In most theoretical formulations, a logarithmic relationship is assumed between the volume of the soil sample and the effective stress carried by the soil particles.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The constant of proportionality (change in void ratio per order of magnitude change in effective stress) is known as the compression index, given the symbol $\lambda$ when calculated in natural logarithm and $C_{C}$ when calculated in base-10 logarithm.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] H is the height of the compressible soil.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] When stress is removed from a consolidated soil, the soil will rebound, regaining some of the volume it had lost in the consolidation process.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] If the stress is reapplied, the soil will consolidate again along a recompression curve, defined by the recompression index.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Cc can be replaced by Cr (the recompression index) for use in overconsolidated soils where the final effective stress is less than the preconsolidation stress.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] where σzc is the preconsolidation stress of the soil.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] This method assumes consolidation occurs in only one-dimension.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Laboratory data is used to construct a plot of strain or void ratio versus effective stress where the effective stress axis is on a logarithmic scale.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The plot's slope is the compression index or recompression index.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] A soil which had its load removed is considered to be "overconsolidated".
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] This is the case for soils that have previously had glaciers on them or that have been affected by land subsidence.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The highest stress that it has been subjected to is termed the "preconsolidation stress".
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The "over-consolidation ratio" (OCR) is defined as the highest stress experienced divided by the current stress.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] A soil that is currently experiencing its highest stress is said to be "normally consolidated" and has an OCR of one.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] A soil could be considered "underconsolidated" or "unconsolidated" immediately after a new load is applied but before the excess pore water pressure has dissipated.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Occasionally, soil strata form by natural deposition in rivers and seas may exist in an exceptionally low density that is impossible to achieve in an oedometer; this process is known as "intrinsic consolidation".
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The process of consolidation is often explained with an idealized system composed of a spring, a container with a hole in its cover, and water.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] In this system, the spring represents the compressibility or the structure of the soil itself, and the water which fills the container represents the pore water in the soil.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] A load is applied onto the cover, while the hole is still unopened.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] At this stage, only the water resists the applied load.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] As soon as the hole is opened, water starts to drain out through the hole and the spring shortens.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] After some time, the drainage of water no longer occurs.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Now, the spring alone resists the applied load.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] (Full dissipation of excess pore water pressure.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The time for consolidation to occur can be predicted.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] This is especially true in saturated clays because their hydraulic conductivity is extremely low, and this causes the water to take an exceptionally long time to drain out of the soil.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] While drainage is occurring, the pore water pressure is greater than normal because it is carrying part of the applied stress (as opposed to the soil particles).
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The theoretical formulation above assumes that time-dependent volume change of a soil unit only depends on changes in effective stress due to the gradual restoration of steady-state pore water pressure.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] This is the case for most types of sand and clay with low amounts of organic material.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] However, in soils with a high amount of organic material such as peat, the phenomenon of creep also occurs, whereby the soil changes volume gradually at constant effective stress.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Soil creep is typically caused by viscous behavior of the clay-water system and compression of organic matter.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Creep typically takes place over a longer time-scale than (primary) consolidation, such that even after the restoration of hydrostatic pressure some compression of soil takes place at slow rate.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] where H0 is the height of the consolidating medium; e0 is the initial void ratio; Ca is the secondary compression index; t is the length of time after consolidation considered; and t95 is the length of time for achieving 95% consolidation.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] Coefficient of compressibility $a_{v}={\frac {\Delta e}{\Delta \sigma _{'}}}$ .
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The compressibility of saturated specimens of clay minerals increases in the order kaolinite < illite < smectite.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The compression index Cc, which is defined as the change in void ratio per 10-fold increase in consolidation pressure, is in the range of 0.19 to 0.28 for kaolinite, 0.50 to 1.10 for illite, and 1.0 to 2.6 for montmorillonite, for different ionic forms.
[src:compaction-geology/consolidation-soil] The more compressible the clay, the more pronounced the influences of cation type and electrolyte concentration on compressibility.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The **Daqing Oil Field** (Chinese: 大庆油田, formerly romanized as *Taching*) is the largest oil field in the People's Republic of China, located between the Songhua river and Nen River in Heilongjiang province.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] When the Chinese government began to use pinyin for romanization, the field's name became known as Daqing.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] It is the largest oil deposit discovered in China and its ability to support China's industrialization changed the country's developmental path.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] Daqing oil field contained 16 billion barrels (2.5×10^9 m3) or 2.2 billion tons in the beginning and has produced over 10 billion barrels (1.6×10^9 m3) of oil since production started in 1960; the remaining recoverable reserves are about 3.6 billion barrels (570×10^6 m3) or 500 million tons.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] Daqing oil field is located in the Songliao Basin, a large sedimentary basin that is in the tectonic framework of the North China-Mongolia tract.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] In 1959, the oil field was discovered by Li Siguang.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] 1205 drilling team) worked on this oilfield.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The first oil well was drilled on September 26, 1959.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] Because the success occurred four days before the tenth anniversary of the People's Republic of China, the field was named Daqing, meaning "great celebration." The discovery of the oil field made the Manchuria region a national center for the oil industry.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] During its 1960 construction during the Great Leap Forward, Oil Minister Yu Qiuli mobilized workers building the Daqing oil field through ideological motivation instead of material incentives, focusing enthusiasm, energy, and resources to complete a rapid industrialization project.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The successful construction of the Daqing oil field despite harsh weather conditions and supply limitations became a model held up by the Communist Party as an example during subsequent industrialization campaigns.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] In April 1960, Yu stated that Mao Zedong's texts *On Practice* and *On Contradiction* should be the ideological core of the Daqing oil field campaign.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The Ministry of the Petroleum Industry shipped thousands of copies by plane so that every Daqing oil worker would have copies and for work units to each set up their own study groups.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The municipality developed around the oil field shared the same administrative body with the oil field production until 1983.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] Daqing oil field was a secret until 1964.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] On February 5, 1964, the central Party promoted Daqing oil field to other industrial enterprises, instructing them to follow the "all-out battle" tactics of Daqing oil field.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] Shortly afterwards, Mao Zedong praised the Daqing oil field at an education work conference, stating that with a "little investment" in a "short period of time" a "great achievement" had been finished.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] *People's Daily* and other state media published numerous articles on Daqing in 1964, extolling the self-discipline of Daqing workers, their study of Mao Zedong thought, and the technical achievements resulting from the democratic participation of workers.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] Most significant among these articles was the April 20, 1964 piece "Daqing People, Daqing Spirit" which *People's Daily* published.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The article compared Daqing to Yan'an, the base area where the Communist Party regrouped after the Long March.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] Promoted as a model of industrial development, Daqing was also promoted as a model of town building.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The field was financed through commodity-backed loans that China obtained from Japan.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The project delivered critical economic benefits because without the production of the Daqing oil field, crude oil would have been severely limited after the Soviet Union cut off supplies as a result of the Sino-Soviet split.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The first two years of the Cultural Revolution resulted in major disruptions to China's petroleum industry and an oil shortage by 1967.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] In March of that year, the People's Liberation Army was called to Daqing to maintain order so that oil production could proceed.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] This made Daqing one of the first places brought under military control during the Cultural Revolution.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] In May 1968, the Daqing Revolutionary Committee was established.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The Daqing Oil Field was among 2,400 central state-owned enterprises transferred to local government control in 1970.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The Daqing oil field continued to be a major driver of economic growth through during the chaotic Cultural Revolution era.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] During the period 1964 to 1980, the oil field accounted for more than half of China's crude oil production per year.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] In 1966, crude oil production in Daqing reached 10 million metric tons and the number of workers at Daqing reached 58,000.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] In the mid-1980s, the oil field generated 3% of China's state revenue through a combination of the profits and tax payments it supplied.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] As of 2013 the field's production rate was about 800,000 barrels per day (130,000 m3/d).
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] Daqing Oilfield Company Limited, based in Daqing, is the operator of exploration and development of Daqing Oilfield.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] From 2004, the company plans to cut its crude oil output by an annual 7% for the next seven years to extend the life of Daqing.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] Output of barrels of oil equivalent of the Daqing Field remained stable at over 40 million tons in 2012, while output at Changqing oil field was over 42 million tons, making it the most productive oil and gas field in China.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] Crude output from the ageing Daqing oilfield is in decline even though the CNPC deployed some non-traditional drilling techniques.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] In 2019, output fell to 30.9 million tonnes from 32 million tonnes in 2018.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] At its peak in 2008, output stood at 40 million tonnes a year.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The production was 30 million tonnes in 2021.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] A new shale oil field was discovered in Daqing Oilfield in 2021, with an estimated geological reserve of 1.268 billion tons.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The Chinese government promoted the success of the Daqing oilfield and the selflessness of workers who built it as part of the face of new the socialist industrial person that China sought to encourage in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The Chinese press urged industrial workers to follow the model of ascetic living practiced by workers on the Daqing oilfield in order to advance China's development of socialist modernity.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] "Iron Man" Wang Jinxi was the most significant model worker in Daqing oil field, and remains one of the most celebrated working class models in China.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] An experienced oil worker from the Yumen Oil Field, Wang was one of the first oil workers to arrive to work the Daqing field in Saertu.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] At Daqing, Wang was one of the first model workers selected by Yu Qiuli due to Wang's devotion to the oil production industry and to competitive work.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] Wang was also the inspiration for Zhou Tingshan, the main character in 1974 drama Chuangye.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The Daqing Oil Field Management Bureau and PetroChina Daqing Company are located in West Town in Daqing.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] In 1964, chief director of the Central Experimental Theater Sun Weishi and her husband, the actor Jin Shan, traveled to Daqing to live and work with the oil workers and their families.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] The next year, the Communist Party journal *Red Flag* published an article by Sun which praised the Daqing people.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] After living in Daqing for two years, Sun Weishi returned to Beijing to produce the play *The Rising Sun*, which was based on the experiences of people in Daqing, particularly Daqing women.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] It is featured as a map in first-person shooter video game *Battlefield 2*.
[src:compaction-geology/daqing-field] It was also featured in a dedicated part of the *How Yukong Moved the Mountains* documentary, "About Petroleum".
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] The process of diagenesis excludes surface alteration (weathering) and deep metamorphism.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] There is no sharp boundary between diagenesis and metamorphism, but the latter occurs at higher temperatures and pressures.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] Hydrothermal solutions, meteoric groundwater, rock porosity, permeability, dissolution/precipitation reactions, and time are all influential factors.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] After deposition, sediments are compacted as they are buried beneath successive layers of sediment and cemented by minerals that precipitate from solution.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] Grains of sediment, rock fragments and fossils can be replaced by other minerals (e.g. calcite, siderite, pyrite or marcasite) during diagenesis.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] Porosity usually decreases during diagenesis, except in rare cases such as dissolution of minerals and dolomitization.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] The study of diagenesis in rocks is used to understand the geologic history they have undergone and the nature and type of fluids that have circulated through them.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] From a commercial standpoint, such studies aid in assessing the likelihood of finding various economically viable mineral and hydrocarbon deposits.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] The process of diagenesis is also important in the decomposition of bone tissue.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] The term diagenesis, literally meaning "across generation", is extensively used in geology.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] However, this term has filtered into the field of anthropology, archaeology and paleontology to describe the changes and alterations that take place on skeletal (biological) material.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] Specifically, diagenesis "is the cumulative physical, chemical, and biological environment; these processes will modify an organic object's original chemical and/or structural properties and will govern its ultimate fate, in terms of preservation or destruction".
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] In order to assess the potential impact of diagenesis on archaeological or fossil bones, many factors need to be assessed, beginning with elemental and mineralogical composition of bone and enveloping soil, as well as the local burial environment (geology, climatology, groundwater).
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] The composite nature of bone, comprising one-third organic (mainly protein collagen) and two thirds mineral (calcium phosphate mostly in the form of hydroxyapatite) renders its diagenesis more complex.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] Alteration occurs at all scales from molecular loss and substitution, through crystallite reorganization, porosity, and microstructural changes, and in many cases, to the disintegration of the complete unit.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] Chemical deterioration of the mineral phase.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] (Micro) biological attack of the composite.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] The hydrolytic activity plays a key role in the mineral phase transformations that expose the collagen to accelerated chemical- and bio-degradation.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] Mechanisms of chemical change, such as the uptake of F− or CO2− 3 may cause recrystallization where hydroxyapatite is dissolved and re-precipitated allowing for the incorporation or substitution of exogenous material.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] Once an individual has been interred, microbial attack, the most common mechanism of bone deterioration, occurs rapidly.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] During this phase, most bone collagen is lost and porosity is increased.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] The dissolution of the mineral phase caused by low pH permits access to the collagen by extracellular microbial enzymes thus microbial attack.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] When animal or plant matter is buried during sedimentation, the constituent organic molecules (lipids, proteins, carbohydrates and lignin-humic compounds) break down due to the increase in temperature and pressure.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] This transformation occurs in the first few hundred meters of burial and results in the creation of two primary products: kerogens and bitumens.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] It is generally accepted that hydrocarbons are formed by the thermal alteration of these kerogens (the *biogenic* theory).
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] In this way, given certain conditions (which are largely temperature-dependent) kerogens will break down to form hydrocarbons through a chemical process known as cracking, or catagenesis.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] A kinetic model based on experimental data can capture most of the essential transformation in diagenesis, and a mathematical model in a compacting porous medium to model the dissolution-precipitation mechanism.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] These models have been intensively studied and applied in real geological applications.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] Diagenesis has been divided, based on hydrocarbon and coal genesis into: *eodiagenesis* (early), *mesodiagenesis* (middle) and *telodiagenesis* (late).
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] During the early or eodiagenesis stage shales lose pore water, little to no hydrocarbons are formed and coal varies between lignite and sub-bituminous.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] During mesodiagenesis, dehydration of clay minerals occurs, the main development of oil genesis occurs and high to low volatile bituminous coals are formed.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] During telodiagenesis, organic matter undergoes cracking and dry gas is produced; semi-anthracite coals develop.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] Early diagenesis in newly formed aquatic sediments is mediated by microorganisms using different electron acceptors as part of their metabolism.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] Organic matter is mineralized, liberating gaseous carbon dioxide (CO2) in the porewater, which, depending on the conditions, can diffuse into the water column.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] The various processes of mineralization in this phase are nitrification and denitrification, manganese oxide reduction, iron hydroxide reduction, sulfate reduction, and fermentation.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] Diagenesis alters the proportions of organic collagen and inorganic components (hydroxyapatite, calcium, magnesium) of bone exposed to environmental conditions, especially moisture.
[src:compaction-geology/diagenesis] This is accomplished by the exchange of natural bone constituents, deposition in voids or defects, adsorption onto the bone surface and leaching from the bone.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Despite their common occurrence in many different landscapes, geologists have yet to reach an agreement on a general theory of exfoliation joint formation.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Many different theories have been suggested, below is a short overview of the most common.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] This theory was originally proposed by the pioneering geomorphologist Grove Karl Gilbert in 1904.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] The basis of this theory is that erosion of overburden and exhumation of deeply buried rock to the ground surface allows previously compressed rock to expand radially, creating tensile stress and fracturing the rock in layers parallel to the ground surface.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] The description of this mechanism has led to alternate terms for exfoliation joints, including pressure release or offloading joints.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] One possible extension of this theory to match with the *compressive stress* theory (outlined below) is as follows (Goodman, 1989): The exhumation of deeply buried rocks relieves vertical stress, but horizontal stresses can remain in a competent rock mass since the medium is laterally confined.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Horizontal stresses become aligned with the current ground surface as the vertical stress drops to zero at this boundary.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Thus large surface-parallel compressive stresses can be generated through exhumation that may lead to tensile rock fracture as described below.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Rock expands upon heating and contracts upon cooling and different rock-forming minerals have variable rates of thermal expansion / contraction.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Daily rock surface temperature variations can be quite large, and many have suggested that stresses created during heating cause the near-surface zone of rock to expand and detach in thin slabs (e.g.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Large diurnal or fire-induced temperature fluctuations have been observed to create thin lamination and flaking at the surface of rocks, sometimes labeled exfoliation.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] However, since diurnal temperature fluctuations only reach a few centimeters depth in rock (due to rock's low thermal conductivity), this theory cannot account for the observed depth of exfoliation jointing that may reach 100 meters.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Mineral weathering by penetrating water can cause flaking of thin shells of rock since the volume of some minerals increases upon hydration.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] However, not all mineral hydration results in increased volume, while field observations of exfoliation joints show that the joint surfaces have not experienced significant chemical alteration, so this theory can be rejected as an explanation for the origin of large-scale, deeper exfoliation joints.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Large compressive tectonic stresses parallel to the land (or a free) surface can create tensile mode fractures in rock, where the direction of fracture propagation is parallel to the greatest principle compressive stress and the direction of fracture opening is perpendicular to the free surface.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] This type of fracturing has been observed in the laboratory since at least 1900 (in both uniaxial and biaxial unconfined compressive loading; see Gramberg, 1989).
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Fractures formed in this way are sometimes called axial cleavage, longitudinal splitting, or extensional fractures, and are commonly observed in the laboratory during uniaxial compression tests.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] High horizontal or surface-parallel compressive stress can result from regional tectonic or topographic stresses, or by erosion or excavation of overburden.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] With consideration of the field evidence and observations of occurrence, fracture mode, and secondary forms, high surface-parallel compressive stresses and extensional fracturing (axial cleavage) seems to be the most plausible theory explaining the formation of exfoliation joints.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Recognizing the presence of exfoliation joints can have important implications in geological engineering.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Most notable may be their influence on slope stability.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Exfoliation joints following the topography of inclined valley walls, bedrock hill slopes, and cliffs can create rock blocks that are particularly prone to sliding.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Especially when the toe of the slope is undercut (naturally or by human activity), sliding along exfoliation joint planes is likely if the joint dip exceeds the joint's frictional angle.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Foundation work may also be affected by the presence of exfoliation joints, for example in the case of dams.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Exfoliation joints underlying a dam foundation can create a significant leakage hazard, while increased water pressure in joints may result in lifting or sliding of the dam.
[src:compaction-geology/exfoliation-joint] Finally, exfoliation joints can exert strong directional control on groundwater flow and contaminant transport.
